    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Thomas L. Friedman (column, Aug. 1) puts the blame for the failed Camp David meeting exactly where it belongs -- on President Hosni Mubarak of Egypt. But this isn't the first time an ungrateful Egypt has taken a leading role in undermining American interests.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Thomas L. Friedman (column, Aug. 1) puts the blame for the failed Camp David meeting exactly where it belongs -- on President Hosni Mubarak of Egypt. But this isn't the first time an ungrateful Egypt has taken a leading role in undermining American interests.</p>
        <p>It consistently votes against the United States at the United Nations while at the same time being offered the most sophisticated American weaponry. With friends like this, America doesn't need enemies.</p>
        <p>MORRIS J. AMITAY  Washington, Aug. 1, 2000</p>
      </block>
